	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64156573"><p>There's no good reason to accept this claim.</p><p>"Gravity's just different according to this fudge factor we put into the calculations to make our other observations make sense" is a reason to keep investigating, but it's not a reason to claim the fudge factor is actually a thing.</p><p>"Gravity is stronger at low accelerations" would indicate there's some equivalent of static friction to overcome before you can move freely in the three spatial dimensions, and there are just so many other things we know with extreme accuracy and precision that would break.</p></div>
