	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64157353"><p><div class="quote"><p>At what point is the failure to find what you're predicting evidence that it's not there?</p></div><p>Never.  When you hypothesize that something exists there's not a game show host that starts a timer and makes you retract if you don't figure out the details before the bell rings.</p><p>That's just not how empirical knowledge acquisition works. Stuff existed almost 14 gigayears before our species came around to detect any of it.  There's probably stuff out there that we will *never* detect.</p><p>DM may be an incorrect hypothesis, but not figuring it out yet is not an argument against it.</p></div>
	</div>

